UID:ai1ec-3957@writersguildbloomington.com
DTSTAMP:20260309T020723Z
CATEGORIES:
CONTACT:
DESCRIPTION:First Sunday Prose Reading and Open Mic\nPresented by the Write
 rs Guild at Bloomington\nThe featured readers are:  Stephanie Kane and Dar
 rell Stone\nCome early to sign up for Open Mic!\nStephanie C. Kane is a cu
 ltural anthropologist and Professor of International Studies in the Hamilt
 on Lugar School of Global and International Studies of IU Bloomington. Her
  ethnographic research on the political ecology of water and ice has led t
 o many publications including two books: Where Rivers Meet the Sea: A Poli
 tical Ecology of Water (2012\, audio 2016) and the new Just One Rain Away:
  The Ethnography of River-City Flood Control (2022). Before the water book
 s\, she published The Phantom Gringo Boat: Shamanism and Development in Pa
 nama (1994) and AIDS Alibis: Sex\, Drugs\, and Crime (1998).\n \n \n \nDar
 rell Stone grew up in Greater Boston\, with an artistic passion for storyt
 elling.  She holds a masters degree in social work from Indiana University
  and a bachelors degree in theatre from Northeastern University. Writing c
 omplements her love for being an observer of human behavior and our enviro
 nment\, which are additionally rooted in her professional careers of socia
 l work and theatre.  Ms. Stone’s essays are known for simply pausing on a 
 moment which can be stunning\, hopeful\, humorous or meaningful to the hum
 an experience.  Ultimately\, she hopes her writing provides a keen eye int
 o the soul of the world around us.  Darrell is currently working on a book
  of essays with photographs for publication and performance.\n \nThe Write
 rs Guild at Bloomington is committed to diversity\, equity\, and inclusivi
 ty.
