 yqohA6xKtD300wxe_JjWRGktap4ohg16X8dvx3AhHwWdl8M</a></div>\n<div></div>\n<d
 iv><span style='font-family: arial\, sans-serif\;'>This poetry class will 
 focus on the haiku form. The “hai” syllable in the word “haiku” connotes “
 play\,” both in the sense of drama\, or theatrics\; and of recreation and 
 enjoyment\, or playfulness. Since “ku” denotes “word\,” or “verbal compone
 nt\,” we will enjoy playing around with words in our haiku crafting proces
 s. To begin this enjoyable process\, we will celebrate spring by reading s
 easonal haiku by the traditional Japanese masters of the form\, such as Ma
 tsuo Basho\, and by Japanese writers of the nineteenth and twentieth centu
 ries\, such as Masaoka Shiki and Mizuhara Shuoshi. Their inspiration\, com
 bined with writing prompts and activities\, should lead to some interestin
 g spring-themed haikus that we will share with each other for constructive
  feedback. Our goal is to produce some verses that celebrate the spring se
 ason and National Poetry Month. </span><br clear='all' /></p>\n<div></div>
 \n<div><span style='font-family: arial\, sans-serif\;'>One of Bloomington’
 s finest and most outspoken poets\, HIROMI YOSHIDA is the author of three 
 poetry chapbooks\, Icarus Burning\, Epicanthus\, and Icarus Redux. Her wor
 k has been included in the INverse Poetry Archive\, and nominated for the 
 Pushcart Prize\, Best of the Net\, the Wilder Poetry Book Prize\, the New 
 Women’s Voices Poetry Prize\, and the Gerald Cable Book Award. She is a po
 etry reader for Flying Island Journal and Plath Profiles\, and a diversity
  consultant for the Writers Guild at Bloomington\, and Constellation Stage
  & Screen. She is also the winner of the “Head-to-Head Haiku Competition” 
 at the 2022 Granfalloon Festival.</span></div>\n<div></div>\n<div class='y
 iv4699123123gmail_signature' dir='ltr'>\n<div dir='ltr'></div>\n</div>\n</
 div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class='jb_0 X_6MGW N_6F
 d5'>\n<div class='P_0 je_fq7'>\n<div class='W_3n93F p_R' data-test-id='att
 achment-item'>\n<div class='I_Z1gjdlg k_w H_7yHc p_R o_h' data-test-id='at
 tachment-container'>\n<div class='D_F ab_C gl_C H_6D6F' style='text-align:
  center\;'><a href='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads
 /2023/04/IWC-haiku-class.jpg'><img loading='lazy' decoding='async' class='
 aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-3984' src='https://writersguildbloomin
 gton.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/IWC-haiku-class-150x150.jpg' alt='' wi
 dth='150' height='150' /></a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</BOD
 Y></HTML>
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ai1ec-4005@writersguildbloomington.com
DTSTAMP:20260309T020723Z
CATEGORIES:
CONTACT:
DESCRIPTION:Writing in the Gallery \n\nEvent by The FAR Center for Contempo
 rary Arts\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTickets · $15\nvia Eventbrite
 \n\nAges 18 plus\n\nAll genders + Experience levels\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nI
 n honor of National Poetry Writing Month\, Women Writing for (a) Change is
  partnering with the FAR Center for Contemporary Arts for an evening of cr
 eative writing in response to Benjamin Rassmusen’s exhibition\, The Good C
 itizen . We will spend time in the gallery space letting the artwork lead 
 us and our writing to new places. We will explore what Rassmussen’s photog
 raphs bring up for us about “the complicated nature of American identity.”
 \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nUsing the practices of Women Writing\, we will create a 
 space to listen and learn from one another. In this facilitated circle\, w
 e will have time to write and time to share our writing in large and small
  groups. This workshop is open to people of all genders and to writers of 
 all types and experience levels. Join us as we explore the intersection of
  our lives and our writing with the visual prompts of Rassmusen’s photogra
 phs.\n\n\nInstructor Bio: Laura Lasuertmer is the Assistant Creative Direc
 tor at Women Writing for (a) Change . She facilitates creative writing cir
 cles throughout Bloomington including at The Academy\, Juniper Art Gallery
 \, Stone Belt\, the Monroe County Jail\, Middle Way House\, and anywhere t
 here are people who want to write in creative community.
