 xt-align: center\;'>Come and meet Scott Russell Sanders. He will read from
  his new book <i>Small Marvels: A Novel-in-Stories</i>. There will be Q&A 
 time for you to ask questions and discuss his work.</p>\n<p style='text-al
 ign: center\;'>His books will also be for sale—cash or check only.</p>\n<p
 > </p>\n<p style='text-align: center\;'>Scott Russell Sanders is the autho
 r of more than 20 books of fiction\, essays\, and personal narratives\, in
 cluding <i>A Private History of Awe</i>\, <i>Hunting for Hope</i>\, and <i
 >The Way of Imagination</i>.</p>\n<p style='text-align: center\;'>He is a 
 Distinguished Professor Emeritus of English at Indiana University and a fe
 llow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.</p>\n<p style='text-ali
 gn: center\;'>He and his wife\, Ruth\, a biochemist\, have raised two chil
 dren in Bloomington\, where they have lived since 1971.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>
 <span style='color: #444444\;'><span style='font-family: BentonSans-Regula
 r\, sans-serif\;'><br />\n</span></span><span style='color: #444444\;'><sp
 an style='font-family: Times New Roman\, serif\;'>Part folktale\, part tal
 l tale\, part comic romance\, </span></span><em><span style='color: #44444
 4\;'><span style='font-family: Times New Roman\, serif\;'><b>Small Marvels
 </b></span></span></em><span style='color: #444444\;'><span style='font-fa
 mily: Times New Roman\, serif\;'> revels in the wonders of everyday life. 
 So\, welcome to Limestone\, Indiana. You won’t find it on a map\, but you 
 may remember visiting the place in dreams\, the rare\, blissful ones in wh
 ich puzzles are solved\, kids flourish\, hard work pays off\, and love end
 ures.</span></span></p>\n<p><span style='color: #444444\;'><span style='fo
 nt-family: Times New Roman\, serif\;'>In Limestone\, Indiana\, a city tuck
 ed away among forested hills\, peculiar things happen\, often in the vicin
 ity of a jack-of-all-trades named Gordon Mills. Centaurs and nymphs shelte
 r in a local cave\, alligators lurk in the sewers\, warm snow falls on the
  Fourth of July\, cornstalks rise higher than chimneys\, and the northern 
 lights shine down on the municipal dump.</span></span></p>\n<p style='text
 -align: center\;'>Age 18 and up.</p>\n<p style='text-align: center\;'><a h
 ref='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Coffe-
 with-Friends.jpg'><img loading='lazy' decoding='async' class='aligncenter 
