X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC '-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//E
 N'>\\n<HTML>\\n<HEAD>\\n<TITLE></TITLE>\\n</HEAD>\\n<BODY><h2 class='yiv48
 64218884MsoNormal' style='text-align: center\;'>Last Sunday Poetry Reading
  & Open Mic</h2>\n<h3 style='text-align: center\;'>presented by the Writer
 s Guild at Bloomington</h3>\n<h3 class='yiv4864218884MsoNormal' style='tex
 t-align: center\;'>featuring Indiana University poets</h3>\n<h3 class='yiv
 4864218884MsoNormal' style='text-align: center\;'>Lisa Kwong and Mahasweta
  Baxipatra.</h3>\n<p> </p>\n<p class='yiv4864218884MsoNormal'><strong>LISA
  KWONG</strong> is the author of <i>Becoming AppalAsian</i> (Glass Lyre Pr
 ess\, 2022) and a member of the Affrilachian Poets. Born and raised in Rad
 ford\, Virginia\, Kwong identifies as AppalAsian\, an Asian from Appalachi
 a. A first generation college student\, she received her BA in English fro
 m Appalachian State University and earned an MFA in poetry from Indiana Un
 iversity. Her poem “Searching For Wonton Soup” was the 2019 Sundress Publi
 cations Poetry Broadside Contest Winner\, and her work has been nominated 
 for a Pushcart Prize\, Best of the Net\, and the Weatherford Award in Poet
 ry. Her poems have appeared in <i>About Place Journal</i>\, <i>Women Speak
 </i>\, <i>Best New Poets</i>\, <i>A Literary Field Guide to Southern Appal
 achia</i>\, and other publications.</p>\n<p class='yiv4864218884MsoNormal'
 ><strong>Mahasweta Baxipatra</strong> lives and teaches in Bloomington\, I
 ndiana. She writes poems and non-fictional prose\, and translates fiction 
 from various Indian languages into English.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p style='text-
 align: center\;'><a href='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/u
 ploads/2023/07/LSP-Juy-2023.jpg'><img loading='lazy' decoding='async' clas
 s='aligncenter size-medium wp-image-4058' src='https://writersguildbloomin
 gton.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/LSP-Juy-2023-300x186.jpg' alt='' width
 ='300' height='186' /></a></p>\n</BODY></HTML>
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ai1ec-4063@writersguildbloomington.com
DTSTAMP:20260309T020723Z
CATEGORIES:
CONTACT:
DESCRIPTION: \nFirst Sunday Prose Reading and Open Mic\nPresented by the Wr
 iters Guild at Bloomington\nThe featured readers are: Rachel Perry and Gre
 ta Lind\nCome early to sign up for Open Mic!\n \nRachel Perry\nSince retir
 ing from the job of Fine Arts Curator for the Indiana State Museum from 20
 03-2012\, I’ve occupied my time researching and writing books about Indian
 a visual artists. Our great state boasts a plethora of fine artists\, from
  the Hoosier Group at the turn of the last century to Regionalists during 
 and after the Great Depression to ground-breaking contemporary artists and
  the resurgence of plein air painters. I’m now turning my attention to “cr
 eative nonfiction.”\nI’ve been lucky to be able to work with Indiana Unive
 rsity Press and/or the Indiana Historical Society to bring several project
 s to fruition\, including Children from the Hills: The Life and Work of Ad
 a Walter Shulz (Artist Colony Press\, 2001)\; T.C. Steele and the Society 
 of Western Artists 1896-1914 (Indiana University Press\, 2009)\; Paint and
  Canvas: A Life of T.C. Steele (Indiana Historical Society Press\, 2012)\;
  William J. Forsyth: The Life and Work of an Indiana Artist (Indiana Unive
 rsity Press\, 2014)\; The Life and Art of Felrath Hines: From Dark to Ligh
 t (Indiana University Press\, 2019)\; and Painter of the Dunes: A Life of 
 Frank Virgil Dudley (Indiana Historical Society\, 2021).\nInfo. about each
  book cover:\nChildren from the Hills: The Life and Work of Ada Walter Shu
 lz \nwas actually my thesis for a Master’s degree in Museum Studies at the
  University of Oklahoma. An artist of the early Brown County Art Colony\, 
 Ada Shulz was one of the few who saw beauty in the people instead of the l
 andscape.\nT.C. Steele and the Society of Western Artists 1896-1914\nAn ac
 ademic exploration into the founding and behind-the-scenes machinations of
  an artist-led group that organized annual traveling exhibitions to major 
 midwestern cities.\nPaint and Canvas: A Life of T.C. Steele\nI call this b
 ook my “T.C. Steele lite.” Written for the Indiana Historical Society’s Yo
 uth Biography series\, it’s an artist biography painted with a broad brush
 .\nWilliam J. Forsyth: The Life and Work of an Indiana Artist\nMy favorite
  artist of the Hoosier Group\, Forsyth’s cantankerous personality and jeal
 ousy of T.C. Steele did not hamper his ability to paint honest portraits a
 nd spontaneous lush Indiana landscapes.\nThe Life and Art of Felrath Hines
 : From Dark to Light\nMy most challenging effort to date\, this biography 
 of a geometric abstract artist who was one of the first students to gradua
 te Crispus Attucks High School\, illuminates the remarkable career of a ma
 n who became Chief Conservator of Smithsonian’s National Portrait Gallery 
 while quietly perfecting his own paintings.\n \n \nGRETA LIND is a lifelon
 g creative whose work spans diverse mediums. She’s appeared in All My Chil
 dren\, Missing Persons\, and the film Rudy. Greta loved raising her two wo
 nderful boys\, acting in The New Harmony Project\, co-facilitating Young W
 omen Writing for (a) Change® Bloomington circles\, and writing her debut n
 ovel\, Split Open\, which was published in 2021 (audiobook coming soon). H
 er recent acting work includes two audio drama series: WFIU’s The Ernie Py
 le Experiment!\, (an Audie Awards® finalist)\, and Starrynight Productions
 ’ The Wonderful Wizard of Oz. Greta was in Cardinal Stage’s production of 
 Our Town as well as Constellation Stage & Screen’s The Importance of Being
  Earnest and Deathtrap. Greta’s most recent role was in PlayZoomers’ Oscar
  & Walt. gretalind.com\n \n \n \n \n 
DTSTART;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20230806T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20230806T170000
LOCATION:Morgenstern's Bookstore & Cafe @ .849 S Auto Mall Road
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:First Sunday Prose Reading and Open Mic
