 ;251\;201\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC '-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//E
 N'>\\n<HTML>\\n<HEAD>\\n<TITLE></TITLE>\\n</HEAD>\\n<BODY><div class='ai1e
 c-event-avatar alignleft timely'><img src='https://writersguildbloomington
 .com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/mic-color-lites.jpg' width='251' height='2
 01' /></div><p> </p>\n<h2 style='text-align: center\;'>First Sunday Prose 
 Reading and Open Mic</h2>\n<p style='text-align: center\;'>Presented by th
 e Writers Guild at Bloomington</p>\n<p style='text-align: center\;'>The fe
 atured readers are: Rachel Perry and Greta Lind</p>\n<p style='text-align:
  center\;'>Come early to sign up for Open Mic!</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><strong><
 a href='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Rac
 hel-Perry.jpg'><img loading='lazy' decoding='async' class='size-medium wp-
 image-4064 alignright' src='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content
 /uploads/2023/07/Rachel-Perry-225x300.jpg' alt='' width='225' height='300'
  /></a>Rachel Perry</strong></p>\n<p>Since retiring from the job of Fine A
 rts Curator for the Indiana State Museum from 2003-2012\, I’ve occupied my
  time researching and writing books about Indiana visual artists. Our grea
 t state boasts a plethora of fine artists\, from the Hoosier Group at the 
 turn of the last century to Regionalists during and after the Great Depres
 sion to ground-breaking contemporary artists and the resurgence of plein a
 ir painters. I’m now turning my attention to “creative nonfiction.”</p>\n<
 p>I’ve been lucky to be able to work with Indiana University Press and/or 
 the Indiana Historical Society to bring several projects to fruition\, inc
 luding<em> Children from the Hills: The Life and Work of Ada Walter Shulz 
 </em>(Artist Colony Press\, 2001)\; <em>T.C. Steele and the Society of Wes
 tern Artists 1896-1914</em> (Indiana University Press\, 2009)\; <em>Paint 
 and Canvas: A Life of T.C. Steele</em> (Indiana Historical Society Press\,
  2012)\; <em>William J. Forsyth: The Life and Work of an Indiana Artist</e
 m> (Indiana University Press\, 2014)\; <em>The Life and Art of Felrath Hin
 es: From Dark to Light</em> (Indiana University Press\, 2019)\; and <em>Pa
 inter of the Dunes: A Life of Frank Virgil Dudley</em> (Indiana Historical
  Society\, 2021).</p>\n<p>Info. about each book cover:</p>\n<p><em>Childre
 n from the Hills: The Life and Work of Ada Walter Shulz </em></p>\n<p>was 
 actually my thesis for a Master’s degree in Museum Studies at the Universi
 ty of Oklahoma. An artist of the early Brown County Art Colony\, Ada Shulz
  was one of the few who saw beauty in the people instead of the landscape.
 </p>\n<p><em>T.C. Steele and the Society of Western Artists 1896-1914</em>
 </p>\n<p>An academic exploration into the founding and behind-the-scenes m
 achinations of an artist-led group that organized annual traveling exhibit
 ions to major midwestern cities.</p>\n<p><em>Paint and Canvas: A Life of T
 .C. Steele</em></p>\n<p>I call this book my “T.C. Steele lite.” Written fo
 r the Indiana Historical Society’s Youth Biography series\, it’s an artist
  biography painted with a broad brush.</p>\n<p><em>William J. Forsyth: The
  Life and Work of an Indiana Artist</em></p>\n<p>My favorite artist of the
  Hoosier Group\, Forsyth’s cantankerous personality and jealousy of T.C. S
 teele did not hamper his ability to paint honest portraits and spontaneous
  lush Indiana landscapes.</p>\n<p><em>The Life and Art of Felrath Hines: F
 rom Dark to Light</em></p>\n<p>My most challenging effort to date\, this b
 iography of a geometric abstract artist who was one of the first students 
 to graduate Crispus Attucks High School\, illuminates the remarkable caree
 r of a man who became Chief Conservator of Smithsonian’s National Portrait
  Gallery while quietly perfecting his own paintings.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </
 p>\n<p><strong>GRETA LIND</strong> is a lifelong creative whose work spans
  diverse mediums. She’s appeared in <em>All My Children</em>\, <em>Missing
  Persons</em>\, and the film <em>Rudy</em>. Greta loved raising her two wo
 nderful boys\, acting in The New<a href='https://writersguildbloomington.c
 om/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Greta-Lind.jpg'><img loading='lazy' decoding
 ='async' class='alignright size-medium wp-image-4065' src='https://writers
 guildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Greta-Lind-300x300.jpg' al
 t='' width='300' height='300' /></a> Harmony Project\, co-facilitating You
 ng Women Writing for (a) Change® Bloomington circles\, and writing her deb
 ut novel\, <em>Split Open</em>\, which was published in 2021 (audiobook co
 ming soon). Her recent acting work includes two audio drama series: WFIU’s
  <em>The Ernie Pyle Experiment!</em>\, (an Audie Awards® finalist)\, and S
 tarrynight Productions’ <em>The Wonderful Wizard of Oz</em>. Greta was in 
 Cardinal Stage’s production of <em>Our Town</em> as well as Constellation 
 Stage & Screen’s <em>The Importance of Being Earnest </em>and <em>Deathtra
 p</em>. Greta’s most recent role was in PlayZoomers’ <em>Oscar & Walt</em>
 . gretalind.com</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p> </p>\n</B
 ODY></HTML>
