BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ai1ec-4164@writersguildbloomington.com
DTSTAMP:20260309T020723Z
CATEGORIES:
CONTACT:
DESCRIPTION:Writers Guild at Bloomington member\nT. Newyear\nRewilding Utop
 ia: An interactive talk + book event\nat\nMorgenstern’s\nNov 10 6:30 PM\n 
 \nFuture Heartland: Indiana Author Releases Starfall\, a New Novel Series 
 Exploring the History and Future of a Midwestern Utopia\n \nThe first nove
 l in a four-book\, history-meets-cli-fi series drops November 7\, 2023 wit
 h its launch event at Morgenstern’s Books in Bloomington\, IN on November 
 10\, 2023.\n \nStarfall weaves together the pleasures and romance of histo
 rical fiction\, unfolding in the same era as Bridgerton but among a very d
 ifferent milieu\, while reveling in double-edged future tech dreams that p
 ay tribute to the sci-fi of Ursula LeGuin and Vernor Vinge. These often di
 sparate genres use different conventions to achieve the same goal: questio
 ning where we are now\, how we relate to each other\, and what our lives m
 ean.\n \nLike many before her\, author T. Newyear stumbled into New Harmon
 y\, Indiana more than a decade ago and couldn’t believe her eyes. The smal
 l\, secluded Indiana town had a sizable collection of 17th-century Italian
  paintings hanging in its town library. It had a labyrinth of trimmed bush
 es at the edge of town. It had quite a pedigree\, including getting namech
 ecked by Lord Byron and Mary Shelley.\nHer explorations over a decade resu
 lted in Starfall (starfallbook.info)\, a sweeping tale set in both the 182
 0s heyday of New Harmony’s utopian experiment and in the not-too-distant f
 uture post-climate change. In both narrative threads\, a woman lands in th
 e town and attempts to unravel a mystery: there are strange pools that for
 m in the woods when the stars fall.\nAbout T. Newyear\n \nFor T. Newyear\,
  the past and the future are two pages in the same book. Combining extensi
 ve research and emotional clarity\, she writes historical fantasies and sc
 ientific romances (as H.G. Wells put it) that explore our complex human an
 d technological relationships\, our connections to what’s greater than us\
 , and our understanding of the past. By playing with historical movements 
 and events\, tech and its impact\, and good ol’ human foibles\, she crafts
  long-form stories that envelope readers in another world or era–and helps
  them feel through our current dilemmas.\n \nA native of the Midwestern US
 \, Newyear grew up in small towns and fading cities\, inspired by nature a
 nd culture\, tradition and radicalism in equal measure. She lived extensiv
 ely in Russia\, traveled alone across Siberia and Mongolia\, and learned h
 ow the other side of the world related to her home turf. With a doctorate 
 in history and area studies\, she has a profound interest in exploring the
  details and lived experiences of the past\, and imagining how those lost 
 moments speak to our collective future.\n\nFor more info and to sign up fo
 r her newsletter\, go to newyearmedia.com\nOther Starfall Events:\nNovembe
 r 11: Fallen Leaf Books | Nashville\, IN | 1-4 PM\nNovember 16: Bartholome
 w Co. Library | Columbus\, IN | 6:30 PM\nJanuary 20\, 2024: Monroe Co Hist
 orical Society | Bloomington\, IN | 1:30 PM\nClick HERE for full press rel
 ease
