BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ai1ec-4206@writersguildbloomington.com
DTSTAMP:20260309T020723Z
CATEGORIES:
CONTACT:
DESCRIPTION:First Sunday Prose Reading and Open Mic\nPresented by the Write
 rs Guild\n\nThe featured readers are:\nMolly Gleeson\nand\nClaire Arbogast
 \nSunday\, Dec 3\, 2023\n3:00 to 5:00\nMorgenstern’s\n849 S Auto Mall Road
 \n\nCome early to sign up for Open Mic!\n\n\nMolly Gleeson was nominated f
 or a Pushcart Prize for her story\, ‘Meishi\, Furo\, Neru’\, which won fir
 st place in The Midnight Oil Magazine’s short story contest in 2020. She h
 as also been published in The Apeiron Review\, Crab Fat Literary Magazine\
 , and Brush Talks\, among others. Molly spent seven years teaching English
  in China\, Saudi Arabia\, and Japan and is now happy to be back in her ho
 metown of Bloomington\, Indiana. She is working on her second novel\, whic
 h she hopes will not remain as unpublished as her first.\n\n\nClaire Arbog
 ast is the author of the novel If Not the Whole Truth [due to be published
  by the end of next year] and Leave the Dogs at Home: A Memoir published b
 y Indiana University Press. Leave the Dogs at Home was winner of the 2016 
 AAUP Public and Secondary School Library Selection and was called an “exce
 llent choice” by the Library Journal—you can find it on the local author s
 helf here at Morganstern.\nResearching and writing If Not the Whole Truth—
 a novel about a young woman who struggles to ferret out her place in the c
 ounterculture of the late 1960s era only to find in 2022 America that ever
 ything she holds dear\, even her own life\, is in jeopardy—re-activated Cl
 aire politically. She became a Planned Parenthood escort (short-lived as I
 ndiana’s abortion ban was reinstated)\, joined the National Organization o
 f Women\, the Feminist Majority Foundation\, and PEN America. She is a mem
 ber of the Writers Guild at Bloomington\, the Indiana Writers Center\, the
  Chicago Writers Association\, a grateful past participant of Women Writin
 g for a Change\, and a recurring donor to the Susan A. Moke Endowment Fund
 .\nShe has a B.A. in journalism from Indiana University and was awarded th
 e 2009–2010 Greer Artist Fellowship Award and a scholarship to the 2009 Th
 e Ropewalk Writer’s Conference Master’s Class.\nClaire’s books\, essays\, 
 and short fiction\, as well as blog posts found on www.clairearbogast.com/
 blog-inside-stories\, challenge attitudes and start conversations.
