 24.png 833w\, https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/
 11/ritter1-768x945.png 768w\, https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-conte
 nt/uploads/2023/11/ritter1-1249x1536.png 1249w\, https://writersguildbloom
 ington.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/ritter1-1665x2048.png 1665w\, https:
 //writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/ritter1.png 1871w
 ' sizes='auto\, (max-width: 244px) 100vw\, 244px' /></a></p>\n<p style='te
 xt-align: center\;'><strong>Anya Royce</strong> is an ethnographer who has
  worked in Oaxaca for 50 years and in Ireland for 15. “I am happiest when 
 I can be a vehicle for the voices of people and the landscapes they occupy
 . Photographs and words work together to support those stories. The storie
 s have found homes in books and blogs and photo exhibits. Sometimes they f
 ind their most resonant shape in poetic forms. I am grateful for the wealt
 h of poets and poetry in Bloomington whose work and company have sustained
  me. Jenny Kander has been a force for poetry and her Linen Weave of Bloom
 ington poets was a gift to all of us. In the same way\, the 5 Women Poets 
 group has allowed my poetic voice to grow with many years of friendship an
 d exchange.”</p>\n<p><a href='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-conte
 nt/uploads/2023/11/royce.jpg'><img loading='lazy' decoding='async' class='
 aligncenter size-medium wp-image-4222' src='https://writersguildbloomingto
 n.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/royce-300x280.jpg' alt='' width='300' hei
 ght='280' srcset='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads/2
 023/11/royce-300x280.jpg 300w\, https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-con
 tent/uploads/2023/11/royce.jpg 698w' sizes='auto\, (max-width: 300px) 100v
 w\, 300px' /></a></p>\n<p style='text-align: center\;'>About a decade and 
 a half ago\, playing Dungeons and Dragons and attending blues jams at Play
 ers’ Pub rekindled <strong>Margaret Fisher Squires’</strong> interest in c
 reative writing. She enjoyed hanging out with the Hart Rock Poetry Series\
 , Upstart Poets\, the Writers Guild\, and of course 5 Women Poets. Fourtee
 n years ago\, Jenny Kander made her feel like a poet by inviting her to re
 ad on the Poets Weave on WFIU. It is only since then that her poems have b
 een published in brass bell: a haiku journal\, The Ryder Magazine\, Fairy 
 Tale Magazine\, and the Five Women Poets’ chapbook\, Birds of a Feather.</
 p>\n<p><a href='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads/202
 3/11/squires1.png'><img loading='lazy' decoding='async' class='aligncenter
  size-medium wp-image-4223' src='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-co
 ntent/uploads/2023/11/squires1-300x228.png' alt='' width='300' height='228
 ' srcset='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/s
 quires1-300x228.png 300w\, https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/
 uploads/2023/11/squires1.png 629w' sizes='auto\, (max-width: 300px) 100vw\
 , 300px' /></a></p>\n<p style='text-align: center\;'><strong>Thomas Tokars
 ki</strong>— with a bow to Abe Lincoln\, Thomas Tokarski states that he is
  a “poet of the people\, by the people\, for the people” with lines and ve
 rses for all.</p>\n<p><a href='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-cont
 ent/uploads/2023/11/tokarski.png'><img loading='lazy' decoding='async' cla
 ss='aligncenter size-full wp-image-4224' src='https://writersguildblooming
 ton.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/tokarski.png' alt='' width='239' height
 ='239' srcset='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/uploads/2023
 /11/tokarski.png 239w\, https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-content/upl
 oads/2023/11/tokarski-150x150.png 150w\, https://writersguildbloomington.c
 om/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/tokarski-230x230.png 230w' sizes='auto\, (ma
 x-width: 239px) 100vw\, 239px' /></a></p>\n<p style='text-align: center\;'
 >Guitarist and songwriter<strong> Jason Fickel</strong> creates music that
  connects the heart and soul of the blues with country music’s wry chronic
 les of loss and longing. Apprenticing with legendary bluesmen in Mississip
 pi\, cutting his songwriting teeth in the clubs of Chicago\, he has forged
  a career as an engaging storyteller and skilled performer.<br />\nFickel 
 was born in Kansas and raised in western Colorado\, the son of farmers and
  avid storytellers. “My family had a lot of country raconteurs\, so when I
  started writing songs I tapped into that deep well\,” Fickel recalls. He 
 has drawn on his family’s trove of tales over the years\, weaving them int
 o his songs.</p>\n<p><a href='https://writersguildbloomington.com/wp-conte
 nt/uploads/2023/11/fickel.png'><img loading='lazy' decoding='async' class=
 'aligncenter size-full wp-image-4225' src='https://writersguildbloomington
 .com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/fickel.png' alt='' width='162' height='226
 ' /></a></p>\n</BODY></HTML>
X-INSTANT-EVENT:1
END:VEVENT
