BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ai1ec-4571@writersguildbloomington.com
DTSTAMP:20260309T020724Z
CATEGORIES:
CONTACT:
DESCRIPTION:As a daughter of Southern Appalachia\, Writer Guild of Blooming
 ton Member Lisa Kwong will be participating in a Zoom event called Soul Wa
 ters Rising: An Appalachian Pause on Wednesday\, October 30\, to raise fun
 ds for Hurricane Helene relief. This is a link for tickets on a sliding sc
 ale or an option to donate if you can’t attend.\n\nHeart Waters Rising: An
  Appalachian Pause\nOnline Benefit Reading for Helene-Impacted Communities
 \nThis gathering will be a time to pause\, reflect\, & collect wisdom\, a 
 time to honor our place & support our communities. Your ticket purchase wi
 ll benefit rural mutual aid organizations working to get people housed & c
 ared for. It will also support Mergoat Magazine\, covering Southern Appala
 chian ecologies on the cusp of catastrophe & futurity. As we heal our comm
 unities\, we must support the publications that care for our communal stor
 ies.\nThe many rivers & creeks interlacing the mountains & valleys of West
 ern North Carolina\, East Tennessee\, & Southwest Virginia swelled to cata
 strophic levels last month as Hurricane Helene dumped unimaginable amounts
  of moisture from the exceptionally warm Gulf. Some 400 miles away from wh
 ere the storm made landfall\, countless homes\, roads\, & even whole towns
  were destroyed throughout our region. Lives have been lost & changed fore
 ver. The riparian ecosystems of the most biodiverse waters in the temperat
 e world have suffered in ways we are still struggling to make sense of.\nA
 s the flood waters receded\, our soul waters rose—in grief for these times
  & the ecological crises that are upon us\, and with love for the land & f
 or one another. As so much has come apart\, Southern Appalachia has come t
 ogether\, ready to envision new ways of being\, to meet the unknown future
  with open hearts. The title for the gathering is inspired by the work of 
 Jaiya John\, who has said\, “I love tears\, I love crying\, I love the sou
 l water rising. …When we connect with ourselves\, when we reunion home & w
 hen we reunion with each other in a pure way\, that’s what naturally happe
 ns\, the soul waters rise.”\nJoin us for an evening of poetry\, spoken wor
 d\, stories\, & music\, as our soul waters rise together in these times of
  trouble.\nHosted by Holly Haworth\nIn partnership with Mergoat Magazine\n
 Benefitting\nRural Organizing and Resilience (R.O.A.R.)\nTri-Cities Mutual
  Aid\nHoller2Holler\n& Mergoat Magazine\nFeaturing\nBlack Atticus   Nickol
 e Brown   Allison Adelle Hedge Coke   Kristopher Drummond   Jesse Graves  
  Raye Hendrix   Laura Hope-Gill   Lisa Kwong   J. Drew Lanham   Rose McLar
 ney   Mark Powell   Ron Rash   Matthew Wimberly\nDisturbance ecology\nwith
  Beverly Collins\nHonoring the rivers Swannanoa\, French Broad\, and Nolic
 hucky with\nTimothy Boyer\, President\, Western North Carolina Muskie Club
 \nLuke Etchison\, aquatic biologist\, NC Wildlife Resources Commission\nWi
 th music by\nMother Marrow\nJim Veteto\, elder seed-saver\nNote: The title
  of this event is inspired by the work of the poet Jaiya John but is not a
 ffiliated with his company Soul Water Rising. To learn more about Dr. John
 \, visit soulwater.org.\nTickets: https://events.humanitix.com/soul-waters
 -rising-an-appalachian-pause/tickets.
DTSTART;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20241030T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20241030T210000
